{
  "local_port": 57178,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What are the alternatives to WalkMe?",
  "response": "WalkMe is a popular digital adoption platform (DAP) that helps users navigate software applications through on-screen guidance, tutorials, and walkthroughs. If you're looking for alternatives to WalkMe, here are some options to consider depending on your needs, such as user onboarding, employee training, or customer support:\n\n---\n\n### **Digital Adoption Platforms (DAPs)**\n1. **Pendo**  \n   - Focuses on in-app engagement, product analytics, and user guidance.  \n   - Great for SaaS companies looking to improve user onboarding and feature adoption.  \n\n2. **Appcues**  \n   - Offers no-code user onboarding and in-app messaging.  \n   - Ideal for product teams looking to create personalized user experiences.  \n\n3. **Whatfix**  \n   - Provides interactive walkthroughs, self-help widgets, and task automation.  \n   - Suitable for both employee training and customer onboarding.  \n\n4. **Userlane**  \n   - Specializes in interactive step-by-step guides for software adoption.  \n   - Focuses on simplifying user onboarding and reducing support tickets.  \n\n5. **Apty**  \n   - Combines on-screen guidance with analytics to improve digital adoption.  \n   - Tailored for enterprise applications and large-scale deployments.  \n\n---\n\n### **User Onboarding Tools**\n6. **Intercom**  \n   - Provides in-app messaging, chatbots, and email campaigns for user engagement.  \n   - Best for SaaS companies focusing on customer communication and onboarding.  \n\n7. **Chameleon**  \n   - Offers no-code onboarding tours, tooltips, and surveys.  \n   - Designed for SaaS product teams to improve user experience.  \n\n8. **UserGuiding**  \n   - A lightweight, no-code tool for creating onboarding checklists, tours, and tooltips.  \n   - Affordable option for startups and small businesses.  \n\n---\n\n### **Employee Training and Support Tools**\n9. **LMS (Learning Management Systems)**  \n   - Platforms like **Articulate 360**, **Adobe Captivate**, or **Docebo** for creating training modules and courses.  \n\n10. **Helpjuice**  \n    - A knowledge base tool for creating self-help resources for employees or customers.  \n\n11. **ScreenSteps**  \n    - Simplifies process documentation and provides step-by-step guides for employees.  \n\n---\n\n### **Customer Support and Knowledge Base Tools**\n12. **Zendesk Guide**  \n    - Builds a knowledge base for self-service customer support.  \n\n13. **Freshdesk**  \n    - Offers helpdesk solutions with knowledge base features for customer support.  \n\n14. **Document360**  \n    - A knowledge base platform for creating and managing self-help resources.  \n\n---\n\n### **Other Alternatives**\n15. **Hotjar**  \n    - Focuses on user behavior analytics and feedback rather than in-app guidance.  \n\n16. **Cognigy**  \n    - An AI-powered chatbot platform for automating customer and employee support.  \n\n17. **Kimbley**  \n    - A no-code platform for creating interactive guides and walkthroughs.  \n\n---\n\n### **Key Considerations When Choosing an Alternative**\n- **Budget:** Some tools are more affordable for startups, while others cater to enterprises.  \n- **Ease of Use:** Look for no-code or low-code platforms if you lack technical resources.  \n- **Integration:** Ensure the tool integrates with your existing software stack.  \n- **Use Case:** Choose a tool that aligns with your primary goal (e.g., onboarding, training, or support).  \n\nEach tool has its strengths, so evaluate them based on your specific requirements.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
